# Localization (i18n) Guidelines

## Structure

Localization files are located in `src/_locales/{locale}/messages.json`.

## Supported Locales

Current translations:

- `en` - English (default)
- `cs` - Czech
- `de` - German
- `es` - Spanish
- `fr` - French
- `it` - Italian
- `ja` - Japanese
- `nl` - Dutch
- `pl` - Polish
- `pt` - Portuguese
- `ru` - Russian

## Message Format

Each message has a key and object with `message` and optional `description`:

```json
{
  "extensionName": {
    "message": "Auto Profile Picture",
    "description": "Name of the extension"
  },
  "extensionDescription": {
    "message": "Automatically fetch and display profile pictures for email senders.",
    "description": "Description shown in add-ons manager"
  }
}
```

## Key Naming Conventions

### Extension Metadata

- `extensionName` - Extension name
- `extensionDescription` - Extension description

### Settings UI

Use camelCase with descriptive prefixes:

- `settingsTitle` - Title of settings page
- `settingInboxList` - Inbox list setting
- `settingContactsIntegration` - Contacts integration setting
- `providerGravatar` - Gravatar provider name
- `previewSection` - Preview section title

### Feature Names

- Use singular form for feature names
- Be consistent across all locales
- Keep technical terms in English if commonly understood

## Adding New Messages

### 1. Add to English (en) First

```json
{
  "newFeatureName": {
    "message": "New Feature",
    "description": "Describe what this text is used for"
  }
}
```

### 2. Use in Code

```javascript
// In JavaScript
const label = browser.i18n.getMessage("newFeatureName");

// In HTML
<span data-i18n="newFeatureName"></span>

// Or with __MSG__ syntax in manifest
"description": "__MSG_extensionDescription__"
```

### 3. Add to All Locales

After adding to English, add translations to all other locale files. If translation is not available, use English as fallback.

## Translation Guidelines

### Keep Consistent

- Use same terminology across all messages
- Maintain tone and style
- Technical terms should be consistent

### Be Concise

- Settings labels should be short
- Descriptions can be longer
- Avoid unnecessary words

### Cultural Sensitivity

- Avoid idioms that don't translate well
- Use neutral language
- Consider cultural context

### Placeholders

Use placeholders for dynamic content:

```json
{
  "avatarFetchedFor": {
    "message": "Avatar fetched for $EMAIL$",
    "description": "Success message",
    "placeholders": {
      "email": {
        "content": "$1",
        "example": "user@example.com"
      }
    }
  }
}
```

Use in code:

```javascript
const message = browser.i18n.getMessage("avatarFetchedFor", "user@example.com");
```

## Common Message Keys

### Actions

- `save` - Save button
- `cancel` - Cancel button
- `reset` - Reset button
- `apply` - Apply button
- `enable` - Enable option
- `disable` - Disable option

### States

- `enabled` - Enabled state
- `disabled` - Disabled state
- `loading` - Loading state
- `error` - Error state
- `success` - Success state

### Settings Categories

- `generalSettings` - General settings section
- `providerSettings` - Provider settings section
- `advancedSettings` - Advanced settings section

## Testing Translations

### 1. Switch Thunderbird Locale

Change Thunderbird language to test translations.

### 2. Check for Missing Translations

All keys in English should exist in other locales.

### 3. Verify Text Fit

Ensure translated text fits in UI:

- Buttons should accommodate longer text
- Labels should not wrap excessively
- Settings page should be readable

### 4. Test RTL Languages

If adding RTL languages (Arabic, Hebrew):

- Test UI layout
- Ensure proper text direction
- Check icon alignment

## Best Practices

### DO:

- ✅ Always include `description` field
- ✅ Use descriptive key names
- ✅ Keep messages in alphabetical order (within logical groups)
- ✅ Test in at least 2-3 languages
- ✅ Use proper punctuation

### DON'T:

- ❌ Hard-code user-visible strings in code
- ❌ Use technical jargon unnecessarily
- ❌ Assume word order is same in all languages
- ❌ Use complex placeholders when simple text works
- ❌ Mix languages in same message

## Updating Existing Messages

When changing English message:

1. Update `en/messages.json`
2. Review and update all other locales
3. Add comment in commit about translation changes needed
4. Consider creating issue for community translations

## Special Characters

Escape special characters properly:

```json
{
  "message": "Use \"quotes\" for emphasis",
  "description": "Example with quotes"
}
```

## Provider Names

Keep provider names consistent and recognizable:

- "Gravatar" (not "GravAtar" or "gravatar")
- "Google" (brand name)
- "DuckDuckGo" (exact brand name)
- "BIMI" (acronym, uppercase)

## Format Specifiers

When using format specifiers in messages:

- Use clear placeholder names
- Provide examples in description
- Document expected format

```json
{
  "cacheSize": {
    "message": "Cache contains $COUNT$ items ($SIZE$ MB)",
    "description": "Shows cache statistics",
    "placeholders": {
      "count": {
        "content": "$1",
        "example": "150"
      },
      "size": {
        "content": "$2",
        "example": "12.5"
      }
    }
  }
}
```
